ce:section.ce:para:
Herein, cotton cloth (CC), commonly used in daily life, was selected as the flexible substrate and a layer of CQDs was uniformly grown on the CC fibers, and then pyrrole was directly grown on CC by in-situ polymerization under Fe3+ initiation to realize the tight bonding between the conductive polymer and the flexible substrate. CQD, as a new type of zero-dimensional carbon-based nanomaterial, is widely popular with its high specific surface area, good electrochemical conductivity, and abundant active sites [39–41]. The specific capacitance (
                        C
                     ) of CC@CQD@PPy electrode is 537.9 F/g at 0.5 A/g, and the assembled CC@CQD@PPy symmetric supercapacitor exhibits an excellent energy density (
                        E
                     ) of 18.7 Wh/kg at a power density (
                        P
                     ) of 125.0 W/kg with a capacitance retention of 77.9 % after 10,000 cycles, providing excellent cycling stability. In addition, the CC@CQD@PPy supercapacitor has excellent flexibility, with almost unchanged electrochemical performance under different bending angles. The all-solid-state supercapacitor composed with hydrogel has good electrochemical properties. In summary, the combination strength and density of PPy on CC were improved by introducing CQD, and the preparation of binder-free CC@CQD@PPy flexible electrodes was realized, which demonstrated excellent cycling stability and energy storage, and greatly promoted the development of smart textiles in the future field of wearable electronics.
